    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.wsujobs.com/postings/24110"/>
    <title>Veterinary Specialist 1</title>
    <content>The available Veterinary Specialist 1 position is an entry level position for a veterinary technician at the WSU Veterinary Teaching Hospital. There is a requirement of at least one year of clinical experience preferably in a veterinary hospital setting prior to applying for this position. Basic veterinary technician skills are expected including but not limited to venipuncture, peripheral intravenous catheter placement, performing basic physical exams, knowledge of appropriate species normal vitals, and appropriate animal restraint. Some familiarity with the common veterinary equipment such as blood pressure monitors, EKG machines, and gas anesthesia machines is also necessary. Incumbents will need to have good communication skills and the ability to work as a team. The Veterinary Teaching hospital currently has 17 different departments that may have a position open. See below for the current department openings. 

*Technician Float/Pool* – This position provides the widest variety of experience in the Veterinary Teaching Hospital. Members of this team may be asked to work in any one of the other services throughout the hospital on any given day. Experience with equine, agricultural animals, and small animals is desired. Training in all departments will allow these team members to become well rounded in all aspects of veterinary technician training. Float techs will also now be assisting our Certified Canine Rehab Practitioner with underwater treadmill therapy, therapeutic exercise, and low light laser therapy. If you like variety and are just as happy working with large animals as you are with small animals than this is the position for you. Both full-time and part-time positions available for Float/Pool Technicians.

*Small Animal Surgery Technician*- The Small Animal Surgery Services are committed to providing the highest quality of care for each and every animal. Led by board-certified faculty, our surgery teams include clinical residents, interns, licensed veterinary technicians, and fourth-year veterinary students. This team works collaboratively with personnel from all services at the hospital, including anesthesiologists, radiologists, and critical care specialists. Not only does this team provide all the basic surgery services for dogs and cats including a full range of orthopedic and soft tissue surgical procedures but also specializes in minimally invasive procedures including, but not limited to: arthroscopy, laparoscopy, thoracoscopy, and cystoscopy. WSU also offers transsphenoidal hypophysectomy, a surgery for treatment of pituitary tumors in dogs and cats. WSU is currently the only veterinary hospital in the country offering this surgery. The surgery tech is involved in set up and tear down of operating rooms, surgical prep of patients, and assisting with specialized procedures. The tech role may be as circulating nurse or scrub nurse depending on the needs at the time. Technicians are also involved in follow up patient care and client education for our surgical patients. 
  
*Small Animal ICU Technician* - The WSU Critical Care is a 24/7 fully staffed fast growing service. Licensed technicians are always on duty helping to oversee and assist with patient stabilization and treatments. This team of outstanding professionals provide compassionate care at the highest level using the latest tools, medicines, and techniques. The staff handles the critically ill and emergent patients with round the clock observation and therapy. Technician duties include peripheral line placement, canine and feline urinary catheter placement, pain assessment, administering constant rate infusions, monitoring vitals including direct and indirect blood pressure, and patient advocacy. 
</content>
    <author>
      <name>Veterinary Clinical Sciences</name>
    </author>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>24111</id>
    <published>2016-03-03T08:03:36-08:00</published>
